==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*medu-'', from Indo-European ''*medhu'' ‘honey, mead’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[mede]], Middle Low German [[mede|mēde]] (Dutch [[mede]]), Old High German [[meto]] (German [[Met]]), Old Norse [[mjǫðr]] (Swedish [[mjöd]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[μεθυ]] ‘wine’, Old Irish [[mid]] ‘mead’, Old Church Slavonic [[медъ]] ‘honey’ (Russian [[мёд]] ‘honey, mead’), Lithuanian [[medus|medùs]] ‘honey’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'medʊ/

===Noun===
'''medu''' ''m''
# [[mead]]
#:''Hwilum æfter medo menn mæst geþyrsteð'': sometimes men are thirstiest after mead.  (''Durham Proverbs'')

